{
  "query": "Besides direct seeding of desired species, what sowing-based interventions can be used to modify grassland species composition?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence on sowing-based interventions includes: (1) Sowing or planting nurse plants alongside seeding/planting of grassland species: one study found community composition became less similar to the target community when nurse species were included in the seed mix; species richness and grass/forb abundance did not change; sowing under nurse plants increased germination and sometimes survival of planted plants (3402). (2) Sowing seeds of nurse plants: one study found reduced similarity to nearby intact steppe, with no change in species richness or vegetation cover (3401). (3) Sowing seeds of parasitic species (e.g., yellow rattle, marsh lousewort): most studies reported increased plant species richness/diversity; total plant biomass decreased in some cases; grass cover decreased while forb cover did not change in one study; abundance of several target species increased in one study (3404). (4) Sowing at higher seed density: studies reported increased forb species richness, increased grass and forb cover, reduced native shrub cover, increased cover of thickspike wheatgrass, and increased seedling emergence of purple needlegrass; sown species cover often did not change, and similarity to a target community did not increase in one study (3405).",
